### рџџ  BUG #6 вЂ” CORS: Allowed Origins Hardcoded, `CLIENT_URL` Env Var Is Unused

**Severity: Medium**

**Affected Files:**
- [server/server.js](file:///e:/p/url_shortner/server/server.js) (lines 94вЂ“103)

**What the code does:**
```js
const allowedOrigin = process.env.CLIENT_URL || "http://localhost:5173";
// в†‘ This variable is declared but NEVER USED

const corsOptions = {
  origin: [
    "http://localhost:5173",
    "https://url-shortener-lovat-gamma.vercel.app"  // в†ђ hardcoded
  ],
  credentials: true,
};
```

**Why it fails:**
- `CLIENT_URL` is read from env but the `corsOptions.origin` array is hardcoded. The env var `allowedOrigin` is **declared but never referenced**.
- If the Vercel domain ever changes (preview deployments, custom domains, redeployments that change domain) the CORS policy will block all requests.
- The hardcoded Vercel URL `https://url-shortener-lovat-gamma.vercel.app` must exactly match the `Origin` header (including no trailing slash). If Vercel adds a trailing slash or changes domain format, CORS silently breaks.

**Recommended Fix:**
```js
const allowedOrigins = [
  "http://localhost:5173",
  process.env.CLIENT_URL,          // use the env var
].filter(Boolean);

const corsOptions = {
  origin: (origin, callback) => {
    if (!origin || allowedOrigins.includes(origin)) {
      callback(null, true);
    } else {
      callback(new Error("Not allowed by CORS"));
    }
  },
  credentials: true,
};
```

