### рџџЎ BUG #9 вЂ” User Model: `select: false` Fields Mutated Directly

**Severity: Minor**

**Affected Files:**
- [server/models/user.js](file:///e:/p/url_shortner/server/models/user.js) (lines 20вЂ“26)
- [server/controllers/authcontroller.js](file:///e:/p/url_shortner/server/controllers/authcontroller.js) (lines 232вЂ“233, 280вЂ“281)

**What the code does:**
```js
// user.js
refreshToken: { type: String, select: false },
refreshTokenExpires: { type: Date, select: false },
```

```js
// authcontroller.js вЂ” login
const user = await User.findOne({ email: normalizedEmail });
user.refreshToken = hashedRefreshToken;  // в†ђ setting field that was select:false
user.refreshTokenExpires = new Date(...);
await user.save();
```

**Why it could fail:**
When `select: false` is on a field and a document is fetched with `.findOne()`, that field is **not projected back** from MongoDB. Setting it on the returned object and calling `.save()` will **write it back correctly** (Mongoose tracks dirty fields). However, when the `refreshToken` controller does:
```js
const user = await User.findOne({
  refreshToken: hashedToken,
  refreshTokenExpires: { $gt: new Date() },
});
```
Mongoose will query against the field (which works), but the returned `user` object will **not have `refreshToken` or `refreshTokenExpires` populated** in JavaScript memory (due to `select: false`). This is why the `logout` controller's check:
```js
if (user && user.refreshTokenExpires) { ... }
```
will **always evaluate `user.refreshTokenExpires` as `undefined`** even though the document has it. The fallback branch always fires.

**Recommended Fix:**
Explicitly select these fields when needed:
```js
const user = await User.findOne({ refreshToken: hashedToken })
  .select("+refreshToken +refreshTokenExpires");
```

