### рџџЎ BUG #10 вЂ” Route Ordering: Wildcard `/:shortCode` Could Catch API Requests if Routes Misconfigured

**Severity: Minor**

**Affected Files:**
- [server/server.js](file:///e:/p/url_shortner/server/server.js) (lines 143вЂ“147)

**What the code does:**
```js
app.use("/api/auth", authLimiter, authRoutes);
app.use("/api", urlRoutes);
app.get("/api/health", (req, res) => res.redirect(301, "/health"));
app.get("/:shortCode", redirectUrl);   // в†ђ wildcard
```

**Why it's risky:**
The `/api/health` legacy alias is registered **after** `app.use("/api", urlRoutes)`. Since urlRoutes doesn't define `/health`, Express will fall through from `urlRoutes` and hit the redirect correctly. However, the ordering means:

If any API path is missing from the route files but a request is made to it (e.g., typo like `/apo/shorten`), the `/:shortCode` wildcard will capture it and attempt a redirect lookup вЂ” returning either a 404 or an unintended redirect. This won't cause a crash but will produce confusing, hard-to-debug behavior.

**Recommended Fix:**
Mount all API routes first and add a catch-all for unmatched `/api/*` routes that returns 404 before the wildcard:
```js
app.use("/api/*", (req, res) => res.status(404).json({ message: "API route not found" }));
app.get("/:shortCode", redirectUrl);
```

